He uses it with his kids
and he uses it himself,

00:43:36.640 --> 00:43:38.396
which made me a little
nervous because those videos

00:43:38.396 --> 00:43:42.944
were for Nadia, and I
didn't know what to do.

00:43:42.944 --> 00:43:44.827
Do I reach out to him?

00:43:44.827 --> 00:43:47.670
I don't think he's listed.

00:43:47.670 --> 00:43:50.349
Then two weeks later, his
chief-of-staff called and

00:43:50.349 --> 00:43:53.371
said you might have heard
Bill's a fan and I was like

00:43:53.371 --> 00:43:55.890
yeah, yeah I heard that.

00:43:55.890 --> 00:43:58.887
They said if you're free,
we'd like to fly you up.

00:43:58.887 --> 00:44:01.185
I was looking at my calendar,
it was completely blank.

00:44:01.185 --> 00:44:03.794
I think I could make some time for Bill.

00:44:03.794 --> 00:44:05.094
I've got to cut my nails,
but other than that

00:44:05.094 --> 00:44:08.333
my schedule is flexible.

00:44:08.333 --> 00:44:11.587
I went up and really
articulated, now at this time

00:44:11.587 --> 00:44:13.056
it was mainly the videos that I was doing,

00:44:13.056 --> 00:44:15.146
I was like look if we
could get some resources

00:44:15.146 --> 00:44:16.952
and I was dreaming about a
five person team and some

00:44:16.952 --> 00:44:19.766
office space, that was
the dream at that point.

00:44:19.766 --> 00:44:22.939
We could build out the
software that I started

00:44:22.939 --> 00:44:24.484
doing with my cousins.

00:44:24.484 --> 00:44:26.049
Students could get practice,
they could feedback,

00:44:26.049 --> 00:44:27.772
we could start building
a community on the site

00:44:27.772 --> 00:44:29.230
so that students can
start helping each other.

00:44:29.230 --> 00:44:31.066
We could build dashboards
for teachers so that

00:44:31.066 --> 00:44:33.401
they could use it to diagnose students and

00:44:33.401 --> 00:44:36.250
leverage class time more effectively.

00:44:36.250 --> 00:44:39.656
Him and then later Google
as well, they were strong

00:44:39.656 --> 00:44:41.282
believers in that.

00:44:41.282 --> 00:44:46.249
Nina: Great. You talk a
little bit about talent

00:44:46.249 --> 00:44:49.472
and creativity in your
book and we talked a little

00:44:49.472 --> 00:44:52.208
bit about this earlier
on, but do you think

00:44:52.208 --> 00:44:56.256
the advent of all these,
not the advent but a couple

00:44:56.256 --> 00:44:59.106
years ago, there were
books focused on talent,

00:44:59.106 --> 00:45:01.435
Talent is Overrated, The
Talent Code, you name it

00:45:01.435 --> 00:45:04.384
and I've read all of
them myself as I have a

00:45:04.384 --> 00:45:06.816
7-year-old who I'm trying
to foster into a talented

00:45:06.816 --> 00:45:09.136
individual, do you think
talent and creativity

00:45:09.136 --> 00:45:14.409
are things that can be in
fact taught to children?

00:45:14.409 --> 00:45:19.062
Sal: I don't think they're...I'm
not sure and in fact,

00:45:19.062 --> 00:45:22.418
I think no one is sure.

00:45:22.418 --> 00:45:26.883
My sense, through both
observation and even seeing

00:45:26.883 --> 00:45:28.870
what's happening there,

00:45:28.870 --> 00:45:30.503
is it's not something that's taught,

00:45:30.503 --> 00:45:32.844
but it's something that can be untaught.

00:45:32.844 --> 00:45:39.516
It can be fostered or
it can be suppressed,

00:45:39.516 --> 00:45:41.145
both talent and creativity.

00:45:41.145 --> 00:45:44.934
I think everyone is born with creatitivy.

00:45:44.934 --> 00:45:49.208
There's not a 2-year-old
on the planet who if you

00:45:49.208 --> 00:45:51.354
introduce a new object
into the room will not

00:45:51.354 --> 00:45:53.639
walk up to that object
and manipulate it in

00:45:53.639 --> 00:45:55.232
every way, taste it, feel
it, see what they can

00:45:55.232 --> 00:45:56.778
do with it, pour something.

00:45:56.778 --> 00:45:58.315
There's not a 2-year-old on the planet.

00:45:58.315 --> 00:46:00.563
There's not a 5-year-old,
actually most 5-year-olds

00:46:00.563 --> 00:46:02.431
will still, a new object
in the room, they will

00:46:02.431 --> 00:46:03.357
engage with it, a new idea,

00:46:03.357 --> 00:46:05.058
they'll ask questions about it.

00:46:05.058 --> 00:46:07.398
Then something happens
where they're taught

00:46:07.398 --> 00:46:09.042
to become more passive.

00:46:09.042 --> 00:46:10.841
To some degree, they're
in an environment where

00:46:10.841 --> 00:46:13.261
questioning is not always cool.

00:46:13.261 --> 00:46:16.561
They're so overwhelmed with work,

00:46:16.561 --> 00:46:19.228
whether it's soccer
practice or homework, that

00:46:19.228 --> 00:46:20.718
there's no time for them to kind of just

00:46:20.718 --> 00:46:22.179
think about something.

00:46:22.179 --> 00:46:24.005
The class is moving on, why
can't they think about it.

00:46:24.005 --> 00:46:26.088
Why am I carrying the one,
that doesn't make sense;

00:46:26.088 --> 00:46:27.594
this seems just like a formula to me.

00:46:27.594 --> 00:46:29.093
They don't have time
for that type of stuff.

00:46:29.093 --> 00:46:33.259
All of these things fall
from this idea of just

00:46:33.259 --> 00:46:35.234
breaking from this Prussian
model, breaking from

00:46:35.234 --> 00:46:36.868
this one pace fits lecture.

00:46:36.868 --> 00:46:39.039
As soon as you take that
out, now all of a sudden

00:46:39.039 --> 00:46:42.119
you can say hey, why
can't we let a student -

00:46:42.119 --> 00:46:44.410
If there's a 16-year-old
some place in the country

00:46:44.410 --> 00:46:47.666
who has just some insight
on like well maybe cancer

00:46:47.666 --> 00:46:50.794
can be addressed and maybe
this is what cancer is,

00:46:50.794 --> 00:46:55.120
too bad, the bell's going
to ring or they have

00:46:55.120 --> 00:46:57.217
an AP test the next day
or they have an exam.

00:46:57.217 --> 00:46:59.228
They're like oh well, I
have too much work to do.

00:46:59.228 --> 00:47:02.377
I quote an admissions officer in the book,

00:47:02.377 --> 00:47:05.015
talk about she was
interviewing a bunch of people

00:47:05.015 --> 00:47:07.064
who were coming to a very
elite college and said

00:47:07.064 --> 00:47:09.536
what do you daydream about
and the one student said,

00:47:09.536 --> 00:47:11.039
"We don't daydream about
anything because it doesn't

00:47:11.039 --> 00:47:13.862
help us to get into
college," and that's tragic.

00:47:13.862 --> 00:47:15.698
It's tragic for that
child, but it's tragic for

00:47:15.698 --> 00:47:18.391
society because it's those
daydreams that eventually

00:47:18.391 --> 00:47:21.596
lead to actual; I'll tell you.

00:47:21.596 --> 00:47:23.989
Khan Academy exists to a
large degree because my

00:47:23.989 --> 00:47:27.157
boss at the hedge fund,
very non traditional for

00:47:27.157 --> 00:47:29.953
that field, had a strong
belief in life work and

00:47:29.953 --> 00:47:34.282
balance and so I had
time to daydream about

00:47:34.282 --> 00:47:35.168
the Khan Academy.

00:47:35.168 --> 00:47:38.176
I had time and my wife
was a resident, a medical

00:47:38.176 --> 00:47:39.885
resident so I felt bad
sitting and vegging and

00:47:39.885 --> 00:47:44.226
watching TV and so I was
able to think about this

00:47:44.226 --> 00:47:47.451
problem and make resources.

00:47:47.451 --> 00:47:49.983
I think anyone is capable of doing that.

00:47:49.983 --> 00:47:51.530
We just have to give them the time and the

00:47:51.530 --> 00:47:53.113
breathing room to do that.

00:47:53.113 --> 00:47:55.283
Nina: Especially now since
it appears, I don't know

00:47:55.283 --> 00:47:59.784
if this was in your book, I
heard it from Tom Freedman.

00:47:59.784 --> 00:48:02.655
Most of the jobs of tomorrow
are going to be jobs

00:48:02.655 --> 00:48:05.323
that are created, not
jobs that currently exist.

00:48:05.323 --> 00:48:09.694
Sal: The Prussian model
started in the Industrial

00:48:09.694 --> 00:48:12.447
Revolution and in Industrial
Revolution, we needed

00:48:12.447 --> 00:48:14.634
probably more educated
people than we needed

00:48:14.634 --> 00:48:16.836
in an agrarian civilization.

00:48:16.836 --> 00:48:18.481
You needed people who
could read the directions

00:48:18.481 --> 00:48:21.088
and have the discipline of
the assembly line and all

00:48:21.088 --> 00:48:24.109
of that, but there was
also a certain passivity

00:48:24.109 --> 00:48:25.976
that you also had to implicate.

00:48:25.976 --> 00:48:27.777
In the farm, there's a
certain independence and

00:48:27.777 --> 00:48:28.862
freedom to it.

00:48:28.862 --> 00:48:30.097
All of a sudden in a
factory, you're doing this

00:48:30.097 --> 00:48:32.291
over and over again.

00:48:32.291 --> 00:48:35.861
One can debate whether
it was explicitly done,

00:48:35.861 --> 00:48:38.481
but there was an element
of instilling that

00:48:38.481 --> 00:48:42.266
passivity and indoctrination
so that people

00:48:42.266 --> 00:48:43.914
could be good workers.

00:48:43.914 --> 00:48:46.498
Before the pyramid was
like this; you needed

00:48:46.498 --> 00:48:48.111
a few knowledge workers
who were doing creative

00:48:48.111 --> 00:48:50.750
things and then you
needed a mass of labor.

00:48:50.750 --> 00:48:53.784
Now the pryamid is kind
of inverted where we need

00:48:53.784 --> 00:48:56.003
a lot of creative people,
in fact all the careers

00:48:56.003 --> 00:48:59.422
now are creative focus and open-ended,

00:48:59.422 --> 00:49:02.720
and you need very little physical labor.

00:49:02.720 --> 00:49:06.441
In that reality, we're
training people for this

00:49:06.441 --> 00:49:08.529
while we need the opposite.

00:49:08.529 --> 00:49:11.948
Nina: Since we are in the
nation's capitol, do you

00:49:11.948 --> 00:49:14.307
have any advice for
Congress or the President?

00:49:14.307 --> 00:49:18.241
How can they best help
bring this vision to life,

00:49:18.241 --> 00:49:19.702
understanding that?

00:49:19.702 --> 00:49:22.033
Sal: That's a very interesting
question because we

00:49:22.033 --> 00:49:25.337
do meet with state officials
and federal officials,

00:49:25.337 --> 00:49:27.449
even in other countries,
ministries of education

00:49:27.449 --> 00:49:29.743
and the one thing that I
don't want to happen is

00:49:29.743 --> 00:49:32.834
right now it's been a very
grassroots, ground up thing.

00:49:32.834 --> 00:49:34.353
People have word of mouthed Khan Academy.

00:49:34.353 --> 00:49:36.044
People have been using it,
parents have been telling

00:49:36.044 --> 00:49:38.415
parents, teachers have
been telling teachers and

00:49:38.415 --> 00:49:41.020
that's good because that's
from people who want

00:49:41.020 --> 00:49:42.340
to make it work and they
figure out and they tell

00:49:42.340 --> 00:49:44.175
us ways to make it work better.

00:49:44.175 --> 00:49:47.330
As soon as you make it top
down, I think it becomes

00:49:47.330 --> 00:49:51.772
no one likes it anymore
and so we want this to

00:49:51.772 --> 00:49:52.804
be very grassroots.

00:49:52.804 --> 00:49:54.310
Whatever I tell people is
just tell people about it.

00:49:54.310 --> 00:49:55.979
Tell people at minimum
they have a free tutor.

00:49:55.979 --> 00:49:57.853
Tell teachers that look,
there might be another

00:49:57.853 --> 00:50:00.211
model that you probably will enjoy more.

00:50:00.211 --> 00:50:02.990
There are ways to reach
more students and on top of

00:50:02.990 --> 00:50:05.909
that and I'm serious about this,

00:50:05.909 --> 00:50:08.696
I think they should set an example.

00:50:08.696 --> 00:50:12.309
It's too easy now in our
society for people to say

00:50:12.309 --> 00:50:14.060
oh, I'm not good at math
and they'll say about

00:50:14.060 --> 00:50:15.802
6th grade math.

00:50:15.802 --> 00:50:17.381
That's math; I don't understand it.

00:50:17.381 --> 00:50:19.891
No one will say oh, I can't
read at a 6th grade level

00:50:19.891 --> 00:50:22.000
or I can barely write.

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:24.252
No one says that, but
you'll hear politicians

00:50:24.252 --> 00:50:26.200
say that, you'll hear
CEOs say that, you'll hear

00:50:26.200 --> 00:50:28.973
people in the press say
that and I think that

00:50:28.973 --> 00:50:30.726
messaging should change.

00:50:30.726 --> 00:50:32.308
Frankly, the only way
that could change is if

00:50:32.308 --> 00:50:33.936
they directly engage with it.

00:50:33.936 --> 00:50:35.808
It's shocking how many
people are engaged in

00:50:35.808 --> 00:50:38.769
education policy when they don't know the

00:50:38.769 --> 00:50:40.056
subject matter themselves.

00:50:40.056 --> 00:50:41.438
Oh, I'm not good at
math, but this is how we

00:50:41.438 --> 00:50:43.696
should test math teachers.

00:50:43.696 --> 00:50:44.803
That's crazy.

00:50:44.803 --> 00:50:46.369
You, yourself, should
engage in the content or

00:50:46.369 --> 00:50:48.863
get adept in the content
and that will be a huge

00:50:48.863 --> 00:50:50.450
signal to society and
I think it'll also help

00:50:50.450 --> 00:50:52.717
inform policy and I think
the more they do that,

00:50:52.717 --> 00:50:56.138
they'll realize it's a
lot less about top down,

00:50:56.138 --> 00:50:58.420
a lot less about the controls.

00:50:58.420 --> 00:51:00.338
The controls that they
do at every iteration of

00:51:00.338 --> 00:51:02.218
ed reform is just about
more controls on teachers

00:51:02.218 --> 00:51:07.643
and it might derisk some
of the weaker players,

00:51:07.643 --> 00:51:11.341
but it also handicaps all the rest.

00:51:11.341 --> 00:51:15.560
It gets to this culture of
everyone getting to mediocre

00:51:15.560 --> 00:51:17.773
and what we really need
to do is go the other way,

00:51:17.773 --> 00:51:19.391
have it be much more grassroots.

00:51:19.391 --> 00:51:22.181
What I point out in this book,
that's an American thing.

00:51:22.181 --> 00:51:24.917
We're a country that's
focused on creativity.

00:51:24.917 --> 00:51:26.321
We're a country that's
focused on people taking

00:51:26.321 --> 00:51:29.058
ownership over their lives,
but our school system

00:51:29.058 --> 00:51:31.401
is a Prussian one, one
that's about passivity,

00:51:31.401 --> 00:51:33.663
one that's about authority.

00:51:33.663 --> 00:51:35.552
Everything about this book is

00:51:35.552 --> 00:51:38.344
let's make our school
system more American.

00:51:38.344 --> 00:51:40.582
Nina: Any final thoughts?

00:51:40.582 --> 00:51:44.926
If you were sitting with
President Obama at the

00:51:44.926 --> 00:51:47.093
White House, aside from asking him to use

00:51:47.093 --> 00:51:50.720
his Bully Pulpit more,
what would you tell him?

00:51:50.720 --> 00:51:53.936
Sal: I'm somewhat about,
I would ask him to;

00:51:53.936 --> 00:51:55.468
this is a somewhat
different dimension, but we

00:51:55.468 --> 00:51:57.356
talk about this in the book.

00:51:57.356 --> 00:52:00.218
I would ask him to make
content for us because

00:52:00.218 --> 00:52:02.142
I think what's happening
right now is the public

00:52:02.142 --> 00:52:04.554
discourse gets so destroyed
in these 30 second

00:52:04.554 --> 00:52:07.329
sound bytes that you can't
have a chance to go deep

00:52:07.329 --> 00:52:09.310
on either side of the aisle.

00:52:09.310 --> 00:52:12.452
Right now, the main adult
learning happens on the

00:52:12.452 --> 00:52:15.654
24-hour news and it's in
these 30 second sound bytes.

00:52:15.654 --> 00:52:17.305
No one really understands
the issues and it just

00:52:17.305 --> 00:52:18.824
becomes very emotionally charged.

00:52:18.824 --> 00:52:21.661
This form factor or this
way, it's a chance for

00:52:21.661 --> 00:52:25.329
Obama to really explain why he makes the

00:52:25.329 --> 00:52:26.808
decisions he does and
maybe the opposition to

00:52:26.808 --> 00:52:30.226
really explain and get
to it and diagram it out

00:52:30.226 --> 00:52:31.852
and even have a quiz
afterwards to make sure

00:52:31.852 --> 00:52:33.036
people are retaining it.

00:52:33.036 --> 00:52:35.052
It would fill in that gap
in learning that frankly

00:52:35.052 --> 00:52:36.392
people are creating.

00:52:36.392 --> 00:52:38.093
Some of our most popular
videos are about credit

00:52:38.093 --> 00:52:40.226
default swaps or about
the healthcare plan or

00:52:40.226 --> 00:52:42.198
the electoral college.

00:52:42.198 --> 00:52:44.279
These are gaps in people's
learning and adults of

00:52:44.279 --> 00:52:45.642
any age want to learn that.

00:52:45.642 --> 00:52:48.207
Nina: Well, it was a
pleasure reading this book.

00:52:48.207 --> 00:52:49.941
It was nice meeting you.
Thanks for joining us.

00:52:49.941 --> 00:52:52.715
Sal: Oh no, it was a pleasure.

